    <h2>Industrial laundry uptime is $5,000 to $15,000 per day in revenue. We treat it that way.</h2>

    <p>Industrial laundry is the contract-throughput operation that processes linens for multiple client facilities. Hotel chains contracted to a single industrial laundry. Hospital linen networks. Restaurant linen services. Capacity runs 100 to 400+ lb per machine, or continuous batch tunnel washers moving 1,000+ lb/hour through wash, rinse, and extract stages. 24/7 production. Contract SLAs that don't tolerate excuses. The parts logistics, the service depth, and the diagnostic complexity are all different from on-premise or coin laundry.</p>

    <p>Our techs service the full industrial laundry lineup across LA County, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. <strong>Milnor</strong> (Pellerin Milnor, Louisiana independent, dominant US industrial brand): 60039M7K, 76032M7K, plus Milnor CBW continuous batch tunnels. <strong>Continental Girbau industrial</strong> (Spanish, premium tier): CL135, CL150. <strong>Wascomat</strong> (Electrolux Professional, Swedish heavy-duty): W4250H high-extract. <strong>Jensen</strong> (Danish premium institutional): Senking series. <strong>G.A. Braun</strong> (Syracuse NY, continuous batch tunnel specialist).</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. <strong>BHGS #A49573</strong> license. <strong>EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410</strong>. <strong></strong> scope for adjacent industrial steam, gas, and HVAC integration. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. Parent: <a href="/commercial/washer-repair/">commercial washer repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Common scenarios</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Top industrial laundry repairs in our 5-county territory.</h2>
    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Drain butterfly valve actuator.</strong> Industrial drain valves cycle 1,000+ times per day, actuator wear at year 4 to 7. $640 to $1,100.</li>
      <li><strong>Inlet valve diaphragm wear.</strong> High water volume cycles. Replace as a set on industrial machines. $480 to $780.</li>
      <li><strong>Tilt mechanism (tilt-discharge industrial machines).</strong> Hydraulic actuator and pivot bearings. $1,400 to $2,400.</li>
      <li><strong>Bearing failure (year 8 to 12).</strong> Heavy-load industrial bearings, expensive replacement. $2,400 to $4,800 with labor; replace-vs-repair threshold.</li>
      <li><strong>PLC and HMI controller failure.</strong> Allen-Bradley or Siemens PLCs with custom HMI panels. $1,800 to $3,500 for full controller service plus configuration reload.</li>
      <li><strong>Steam injection valve (steam-heated systems).</strong> Boiler-system coordination required. $480 to $780 valve plus $200 to $400 boiler-side coordination.</li>
      <li><strong>Tunnel transfer mechanism (continuous batch systems).</strong> Most complex industrial repair. $2,400 to $5,000+ depending on scope.</li>
      <li><strong>Conveyor belt (continuous batch tunnels).</strong> $1,200 to $2,800 belt plus alignment.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Field observations</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Three things we see on industrial laundry calls that aren't in the manual.</h2>

    <p><strong>1. PLC firmware backups are the single most common operator gap.</strong> Industrial machines run custom programs on Allen-Bradley or Siemens PLCs: cycle profiles tuned to the operator's chemical formulation, water temperature targets, and contract throughput requirements. When the PLC controller fails and we install a replacement, restoring the program is the difference between 90 minutes of integration work and 8 hours of reverse-engineering. Operators who keep a current PLC backup save thousands in service time. Operators who don't, pay for the PLC engineer time it takes to recreate the program from production logs and operator memory. We ask about backups on every industrial diagnostic.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Bearing failure is the year-8-to-12 replace-vs-repair threshold.</strong> Industrial bearings are heavy, expensive, and labor-intensive to replace. When a 200 lb capacity Milnor or Continental Girbau industrial machine reaches year 8 to 12 and the front bearing fails, the math gets interesting: $2,400 to $4,800 bearing replacement on a unit that retails $40,000 to $80,000 new. The economics usually favor repair, but if the machine has had multiple major repairs already (drain valve, tilt mechanism, PLC), the operator may have a legitimate replace conversation. We do that math on-site.</p>

    <p><strong>3. Steam-side troubleshooting requires boiler-system coordination.</strong> Steam-heated industrial machines depend on upstream boiler pressure and quality, but the boiler is usually serviced by a different specialty contractor. When a "steam injection valve" complaint actually traces to inadequate boiler pressure or wet steam from boiler carryover, the fix isn't on the machine side. We coordinate with the operator's boiler-system contractor to verify upstream conditions before quoting machine-side parts. About 25% of "steam valve" complaints we diagnose end up boiler-side.</p>
  </div>
</section>

